                <p>The best case for Bubble Sort occurs when the array is already sorted. In this scenario, it only needs to make one pass to confirm it's sorted, performing <span class="notation">n</span> comparisons. This means the time grows directly proportional to the input size. However, this is rarely the case in practice for unsorted data.</p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>As you can see from the visualization, Bubble Sort's <span class="notation">O(n²)</span> average-case complexity means it falls far behind Merge Sort and Quick Sort as the number of elements (<span class="notation">n</span>) increases, making it a poor choice for general-purpose sorting.</p>
