            <h2>Discussion: The Singleton Design Pattern</h2>

            <p>The Singleton pattern ensures that a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to that instance. In our theme management example, it guarantees that there's only one <code>ThemeManager</code> controlling the application's theme state.</p>

            <h3>Advantages of Singletons:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Controlled Access to Single Instance:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Ensures that a class has only one instance, preventing multiple, potentially conflicting, instances from being created.</li>
                        <li>Provides a centralized point of control for a resource or service, like our theme manager.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Global Access Point:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>The single instance can be accessed from anywhere in the application, simplifying access to shared resources.</li>
                        <li>No need to pass the instance around as a parameter to multiple functions or components.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Lazy Initialization:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>The instance can be created only when it's first requested, saving resources if the instance is not always needed.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Resource Management:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Useful for managing unique resources such as database connections, loggers, or, as in this case, application-wide configuration like themes.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Disadvantages of Singletons:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Global State and Tight Coupling:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Introduces global state, which can make debugging difficult as any part of the application can modify it.</li>
                        <li>Leads to tight coupling between the client code and the singleton. Client code directly calls <code>Singleton.getInstance()</code>, making it hard to swap out implementations or test components in isolation.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Testability Issues:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Difficult to mock or stub singletons for unit testing, as their global nature means they carry state between tests, leading to non-deterministic test results.</li>
                        <li>Injecting a mock singleton is often not straightforward.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Violates Single Responsibility Principle:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>A singleton class is responsible for both its own functionality and for managing its single instance.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Hidden Dependencies:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Dependencies on singletons are often not explicit in method signatures, making it harder to understand a component's requirements.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Scalability Concerns (in some contexts):</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>While not directly applicable to a simple client-side theme manager, in server-side applications, singletons can become bottlenecks or introduce concurrency issues if not handled carefully.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3>When to Consider Alternatives (Dependency Injection, etc.):</h3>
            <p>Given the disadvantages, singletons should be used sparingly and with caution. Often, other patterns offer better solutions, especially in larger, more complex applications.</p>

            <blockquote>
                "Singletons are often considered an anti-pattern in modern software development, particularly in environments that value testability and loose coupling."
            </blockquote>

            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Dependency Injection (DI):</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> For most scenarios where a component needs to use another service or object. Instead of the component creating or looking up its dependencies (like a singleton), dependencies are "injected" into it from an external source (e.g., a DI container, or simply passed as constructor arguments).</li>
                        <li><strong>Advantages:</strong> Improves testability (easy to inject mocks), reduces coupling, makes dependencies explicit, and enhances maintainability.</li>
                        <li><strong>Example:</strong> Instead of <code>new MyComponent(ThemeManager.getInstance())</code>, you'd have <code>new MyComponent(themeManagerInstance)</code> where <code>themeManagerInstance</code> is provided externally.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Module Pattern (or ES Modules):</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> For organizing code and creating private scope, often used to encapsulate utility functions or state that doesn't strictly need a "class" interface. In JavaScript, ES Modules inherently provide a form of singleton-like behavior where each module is evaluated once and its exports are shared.</li>
                        <li><strong>Advantages:</strong> Clean encapsulation, avoids global namespace pollution, and in ES Modules, provides clear import/export contracts.</li>
                        <li><strong>Example:</strong> A file <code>theme-service.js</code> exporting functions like <code>getTheme()</code> and <code>setTheme()</code>. When imported, the module's internal state (like the current theme) is shared across all imports.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Service Locator:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> When you need to retrieve services by name from a central registry. It's an alternative to DI, but often considered less preferable as it can hide dependencies similar to singletons.</li>
                        <li><strong>Advantages:</strong> Centralized service retrieval.</li>
                        <li><strong>Disadvantages:</strong> Hides dependencies, can make testing harder than DI.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Passing State as Props (React/Vue/etc.):</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> In component-based UI frameworks, state is often passed down through component props. For global state, context APIs or state management libraries (Redux, Vuex, Zustand) are preferred.</li>
                        <li><strong>Advantages:</strong> Clear data flow, predictable state changes, excellent testability.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                In our simple client-side theme toggle, a Singleton is arguably acceptable due to its straightforward nature and the limited scope of the "global" state. However, for more complex applications, especially those with extensive testing requirements, Dependency Injection or a well-structured module pattern would generally be a more robust and maintainable choice.
            </p>
