                        <strong>IP Address Literals:</strong> The domain part can technically be an IP address literal (e.g., <code>user@[192.168.1.1]</code> or <code>user@[IPv6:2001:db8::1]</code>). While rarely used in practice, it's valid per RFCs.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Internationalized Domain Names (IDN):</strong> While modern systems use Punycode (e.g., <code>xn--mller-kva.com</code>), the display often shows the original Unicode. A regex would need to account for both or rely on external libraries.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Ambiguity and Readability:</strong> A regex attempting to cover even a significant portion of RFCs becomes incredibly long, complex, and virtually unreadable. This makes it difficult to maintain, debug, and ensure correctness. Many "RFC-compliant" regexes you find online are either incomplete or suffer from catastrophic backtracking issues.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Contextual Rules:</strong> Some RFC rules are contextual. For example, a dot <code>.</code> cannot be the first or last character of the local-part, nor can two dots appear consecutively (<code>..</code>). While regex can handle some of these, combining them all becomes unwieldy.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>What Validation *Really* Means:</strong> An email address is essentially a routing instruction. The only true way to "validate" an email address is to send an email to it and see if it's received and confirmed by the user. Everything else is just a guess at its format or existence.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Better Alternatives for Production Use:</h3>
        <p>Given the limitations, here's what's recommended for robust email validation in production environments:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <strong>Leverage Built-in Browser Validation (Initial Client-Side):</strong>
                <p>Browsers have a basic, but often sufficient, level of validation for <code>&lt;input type="email"&gt;</code>. This handles many common cases and is a good first line of defense. It's what this demo uses implicitly for some base checks, though our JS adds more.</p>
                <pre><code>&lt;input type="email" required&gt;</code></pre>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Use a Robust Library/API (Server-Side):</strong>
                <p>For server-side validation, use a battle-tested library in your chosen programming language that understands the nuances of email RFCs. These libraries often involve more than just regex; they might parse the address into its components, check for valid domain syntax, and sometimes even perform DNS lookups (MX records).</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Python:</strong> <code>email.utils.parseaddr</code> (part of the standard library, but for parsing, not full validation), <code>email_validator</code> package.</li>
                    <li><strong>PHP:</strong> <code>filter_var($email, FILTER_VALIDATE_EMAIL)</code> is excellent and handles many RFC complexities.</li>
                    <li><strong>JavaScript (Node.js):</strong> Libraries like <code>validator.js</code> (specifically <code>validator.isEmail()</code>) or more specialized email parsing libraries.</li>
                    <li><strong>Java:</strong> Apache Commons Validator.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Send a Confirmation Email (The Gold Standard):</strong>
                <p>This is the only method that truly verifies two things:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>The email address is syntactically valid enough to receive mail.</li>
                    <li>The user actually owns or has access to that email address.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Implement a "double opt-in" or "email verification" flow where a unique link is sent to the provided address, and the user must click it to confirm.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Domain Verification (MX Records):</strong>
                <p>For an extra layer, you can perform a DNS lookup for MX (Mail Exchange) records on the domain part of the email address. If no MX records exist, it's highly unlikely mail can be delivered to that domain. This is often part of more comprehensive validation libraries/services.</p>
            </li>
        </ol>
        <p>
            In summary, while a client-side regex like the one in this demo can provide good immediate feedback for common cases, <strong>never rely solely on client-side regex for security or critical data integrity</strong>. Always perform robust validation on the server, ideally with a combination of a good library and an email confirmation step.
        </p>
