    <div class="recursion-explanation">
        <h2>Understanding Recursion Depth and Limits</h2>
        <p>
            This fractal tree is drawn using a <strong>recursive function</strong>. A recursive function is one that calls itself to solve smaller instances of the same problem. In our case, drawing a branch involves drawing two smaller branches at its end, and those smaller branches in turn draw even smaller ones, and so on.
        </p>
        <p>
            The <strong>recursion depth</strong> (controlled by the slider above) determines how many times this self-calling process can repeat. Each level of recursion adds a "frame" to the program's <strong>call stack</strong>.
        </p>
        <h3>The Call Stack and Stack Overflow</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Call Stack:</strong> When a function is called, information about that call (like local variables and where to return to when the function finishes) is pushed onto a data structure called the call stack.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Stack Overflow:</strong> If a recursive function calls itself too many times without reaching a base case (a condition where it stops recursing), the call stack can grow too large, exceeding the memory allocated for it. This results in a <strong>"Stack Overflow" error</strong>, crashing the program.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>JavaScript Limits:</strong> Browsers and Node.js environments have specific limits on recursion depth (i.e., the maximum size of the call stack). These limits vary but are typically in the range of thousands to tens of thousands of calls. For example, Chrome might allow around 10,000-15,000 recursive calls. While our fractal tree's depth of 12 is far from this limit, it's a critical concept for deeper recursion.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Practical Solutions for Deep Recursion</h3>
        <p>
            When a problem naturally lends itself to recursion but requires depths that might exceed stack limits, several strategies can be employed:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Iterative Conversion:</strong> Any recursive algorithm can be rewritten iteratively using explicit data structures like a <strong>stack</strong> (or queue) to manage the state that would otherwise be handled by the call stack. This is often more complex to implement but avoids stack overflow.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Tail Call Optimization (TCO):</strong> Some programming languages and environments can optimize "tail calls" (where the recursive call is the very last operation in the function) by reusing the current stack frame instead of creating a new one. This effectively turns recursion into iteration at the machine level, preventing stack overflow. However, <strong>JavaScript engines do not currently guarantee TCO</strong> for general recursion, though it was part of an earlier ECMAScript specification (ES6) but later removed due to implementation complexities across engines.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Memoization/Dynamic Programming:</strong> For problems with overlapping subproblems, storing the results of expensive function calls (memoization) can reduce the number of recursive calls significantly, though it doesn't directly address stack depth for a pure tree generation like this.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Adjusting Environment Limits:</strong> In some environments (like Node.js), you can increase the stack size limit, but this is generally a workaround and not a robust solution for fundamentally deep recursion.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            For our fractal tree, a depth of 12 is well within safe limits, but understanding these concepts is crucial for developing robust recursive algorithms for more complex or larger-scale problems.
        </p>
    </div>

    <script>
        const canvas = document.getElementById('fractalCanvas');
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
        const depthSlider = document.getElementById('depthSlider');
        const currentDepthSpan = document.getElementById('currentDepth');

        const CANVAS_WIDTH = canvas.width;
        const CANVAS_HEIGHT = canvas.height;

        // Function to clear the canvas and draw the tree
        function drawTree(depth) {
            ctx.clearRect(0, 0, CANVAS_WIDTH, CANVAS_HEIGHT);
            ctx.strokeStyle = '#5c3a21'; // Brown for branches
            ctx.lineWidth = 2;

            // Start drawing from the bottom center of the canvas
            // Initial branch: x, y, length, angle (upwards)
            drawBranch(CANVAS_WIDTH / 2, CANVAS_HEIGHT, 120, -Math.PI / 2, depth);
        }

        // Recursive function to draw a branch
        function drawBranch(startX, startY, length, angle, currentDepth) {
            // Base case: If currentDepth is 0, stop recursing
            if (currentDepth === 0) {
                return;
            }

            // Calculate end point of the branch
            const endX = startX + length * Math.cos(angle);
            const endY = startY + length * Math.sin(angle);

            // Draw the current branch
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(startX, startY);
            ctx.lineTo(endX, endY);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Recursively draw two smaller branches at the end of the current branch
            // Adjust length, angle, and decrease depth for the next level
            const newLength = length * 0.7; // Each new branch is 70% of the parent's length
            const newDepth = currentDepth - 1;

            // Branch 1: to the left (relative to current angle)
            // Angle adjustment: -Math.PI / 6 (30 degrees left)
            drawBranch(endX, endY, newLength, angle - Math.PI / 6, newDepth);

            // Branch 2: to the right (relative to current angle)
            // Angle adjustment: +Math.PI / 6 (30 degrees right)
            drawBranch(endX, endY, newLength, angle + Math.PI / 6, newDepth);
        }

        // Event listener for the slider
        depthSlider.addEventListener('input', () => {
            const currentDepth = parseInt(depthSlider.value);
            currentDepthSpan.textContent = currentDepth;
            drawTree(currentDepth);
        });

        // Initial draw when the page loads
        drawTree(parseInt(depthSlider.value));
    </script>
</body>
