        </p>

        <h3>What is the Call Stack?</h3>
        <p>
            When any function is called in a program (recursive or not), the JavaScript engine (or any programming language runtime) places information about that function call onto a data structure called the <strong>call stack</strong>. This information, called a <strong>stack frame</strong>, includes:
            <ul>
                <li>The arguments passed to the function.</li>
                <li>Local variables declared within the function.</li>
                <li>The return address (where the program should continue execution after the function finishes).</li>
            </ul>
            When a function finishes executing, its stack frame is popped off the stack, and execution returns to the previous function's context.
        </p>

        <h3>Why Deep Recursion Causes Stack Overflow Errors</h3>
        <p>
            A "stack overflow" error occurs when the call stack runs out of space. This happens during deep recursion because each recursive call adds a new stack frame to the call stack. If the recursion goes too deep (i.e., the function calls itself too many times without returning), the stack will eventually grow beyond its allocated memory limit.
        </p>
        <p>
            The maximum depth varies depending on the JavaScript engine (browser), operating system, and available memory. For example, in browsers, it's often around a few thousand calls, but can be much lower for complex stack frames.
            When the stack overflows, the program typically crashes with an error like "Maximum call stack size exceeded."
        </p>

        <h3>Practical Solutions to Avoid Stack Overflow</h3>

        <h4>1. Iterative Approaches (Loops and Explicit Stacks)</h4>
        <p>
            Most recursive problems can be refactored into iterative solutions using loops. For problems that naturally involve exploring branches (like trees or graphs), you can use an explicit stack (an array in JavaScript) to manage the pending tasks, rather than relying on the implicit call stack.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Example using an explicit stack for tree traversal:</strong>
            Instead of:
            <pre><code>function recursiveTraversal(node) {
    if (!node) return;
    // process node
    recursiveTraversal(node.left);
    recursiveTraversal(node.right);
}</code></pre>
            You could do:
            <pre><code>function iterativeTraversal(root) {
    let stack = [root];
    while (stack.length > 0) {
        let node = stack.pop();
        if (node) {
            // process node
            stack.push(node.right); // Push right first so left is processed first (LIFO)
            stack.push(node.left);
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
            This approach manages the "pending calls" manually, preventing the call stack from growing too large.
        </p>

        <h4>2. Tail Call Optimization (TCO)</h4>
        <p>
            Tail Call Optimization is a compiler optimization technique where, if the last operation in a function is a call to another function (or itself), the current stack frame can be reused or discarded instead of creating a new one. This effectively turns certain types of recursion into iteration, preventing stack overflow.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Conditions for TCO (Tail Position):</strong> A function call is in "tail position" if its return value is immediately returned by the calling function, without any further operations being performed on it.
            <pre><code>// NOT tail call: result of 'sum(n-1)' is used in an addition
function sum(n, acc = 0) {
    if (n === 0) return acc;
    return n + sum(n - 1, acc);
}

// Tail call: result of 'sumTail(n-1)' is directly returned
function sumTail(n, acc = 0) {
    if (n === 0) return acc;
    return sumTail(n - 1, acc + n);
}</code></pre>
        </p>
