        <h2>Understanding Recursion: Beyond the Surface</h2>

        <p>Recursion is a programming technique where a function calls itself, directly or indirectly, to solve a problem. It's often described as breaking a problem down into smaller, self-similar subproblems until a base case is reached. While that's true, it barely scratches the surface of its elegance and potential pitfalls.</p>

        <h3>The Core Mechanism: How Recursion Works (The Call Stack)</h3>
        <p>When a function is called, the system creates a <strong>stack frame</strong> (or activation record) on the <strong>call stack</strong>. This frame contains vital information:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Local variables:</strong> The values of variables specific to that function call.</li>
            <li><strong>Parameters:</strong> The arguments passed into the function.</li>
            <li><strong>Return address:</strong> The memory location where the program should resume execution after the function finishes.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>In recursion, each recursive call adds a new stack frame on top of the previous one. This creates a "stack" of pending function calls. When a base case is hit, the function returns, and its stack frame is popped off. The program then returns to the caller's return address, effectively unwinding the stack.</p>
        <p>Consider the factorial function <code>n! = n * (n-1)!</code>:</p>
        <pre><code>function factorial(n) {
    if (n === 0) { // Base Case
        return 1;
    }
    return n * factorial(n - 1); // Recursive Step
}

// factorial(3) trace:
// 1. factorial(3) called. Stack: [f(3)]
// 2. Calls factorial(2). Stack: [f(3), f(2)]
// 3. Calls factorial(1). Stack: [f(3), f(2), f(1)]
// 4. Calls factorial(0). Stack: [f(3), f(2), f(1), f(0)]
// 5. factorial(0) returns 1. Stack: [f(3), f(2), f(1)]
// 6. factorial(1) receives 1, calculates 1 * 1 = 1, returns 1. Stack: [f(3), f(2)]
// 7. factorial(2) receives 1, calculates 2 * 1 = 2, returns 2. Stack: [f(3)]
// 8. factorial(3) receives 2, calculates 3 * 2 = 6, returns 6. Stack: []
</code></pre>

        <h3>The Peril: Stack Overflow Risks from Deep Recursion</h3>
        <p>The call stack has a finite amount of memory allocated to it by the operating system (or JavaScript engine in a browser). If a recursive function calls itself too many times without reaching a base case, it can exhaust this allocated memory. This is known as a <strong>Stack Overflow Error</strong>.</p>
        <p>Each stack frame, while small, consumes memory. Deep recursion means thousands or even millions of frames piling up, eventually exceeding the stack's capacity. The browser (or runtime) detects this and terminates the program to prevent further memory corruption or instability.</p>
        <p>For our fractal tree, a depth of 12 is relatively shallow. But imagine trying to generate a tree with a depth of 10,000 using this pure recursive approach. You'd hit a stack overflow very quickly.</p>

        <h3>Real Practical Solutions to Mitigate Stack Overflow</h3>

        <h4>1. Iteration (Loop-based Solutions)</h4>
        <p>The most common and often most performant solution is to convert recursive algorithms into iterative ones. This eliminates the call stack overhead entirely, using a custom stack (e.g., an array) or simply loops to manage state.</p>
        <pre><code class="language-javascript">
// Example: Iterative Depth-First Traversal (DFS) for a tree
function iterativeDFS(root) {
    if (!root) return;
    const stack = [root]; // Our custom stack
    while (stack.length > 0) {
        const node = stack.pop();
        console.log(node.value); // Process the node
        // Push children in reverse order for correct processing order
        if (node.right) stack.push(node.right);
        if (node.left) stack.push(node.left);
    }
}
