        <h3>Proving Understanding: Why Recursion is More Than Just Loops</h3>
        <p>While many recursive problems can be solved iteratively, recursion offers:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Clarity and Readability:</strong> For problems that are naturally defined recursively (like tree traversals, fractal generation, quicksort, mergesort), the recursive solution often mirrors the problem definition directly, making the code more elegant and easier to understand. The fractal tree is a prime example: "a tree is a trunk with two smaller trees on top."</li>
            <li><strong>Reduced State Management:</strong> The call stack automatically handles saving and restoring the context (local variables, return addresses) for each subproblem. In an iterative solution, you often have to explicitly manage a stack or queue to keep track of pending work.</li>
            <li><strong>Mathematical Induction Parallel:</strong> Recursion aligns perfectly with proofs by induction: define a base case and show that if it works for <code>k</code>, it works for <code>k+1</code>. This formal elegance can lead to more robust algorithms.</li>
            <li><strong>Exploring Problem Spaces:</strong> Algorithms like backtracking and depth-first search (DFS) often find their most natural and concise expression through recursion, as they inherently explore branching paths.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The challenge isn't just to write a recursive function, but to understand <em>when</em> it's the right tool, its performance implications, and how to safeguard against its inherent risks. The fractal tree demonstrates its power for problems with self-similar substructures, where the elegance of expressing "do the same thing, but smaller" is unmatched.</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        const canvas = document.getElementById('fractalCanvas');
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
        const depthSlider = document.getElementById('depthSlider');
        const currentDepthSpan = document.getElementById('currentDepth');

        // Initial canvas setup
        ctx.strokeStyle = '#fff'; // White branches
        ctx.lineWidth = 2;
        ctx.lineCap = 'round';

        // Function to draw a single branch
        function drawBranch(startX, startY, length, angle, depth) {
            // Base case: Stop drawing when depth is 0 or less
            if (depth <= 0) {
                return;
            }

            // Calculate end point of the current branch
            const endX = startX + length * Math.cos(angle);
            const endY = startY + length * Math.sin(angle);

            // Draw the current branch
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(startX, startY);
            ctx.lineTo(endX, endY);
            ctx.stroke();

            // Recursive step: Draw two smaller branches at the end of the current branch
            // Each new branch is shorter and at a different angle
            const newLength = length * 0.75; // Shorter branches
            const branchAngle = Math.PI / 6; // Angle offset for new branches (30 degrees)

            // Draw left branch
            drawBranch(endX, endY, newLength, angle - branchAngle, depth - 1);
            // Draw right branch
            drawBranch(endX, endY, newLength, angle + branchAngle, depth - 1);
        }

        // Function to clear canvas and draw the tree
        function drawTree() {
            ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height); // Clear the entire canvas

            const maxDepth = parseInt(depthSlider.value);
            currentDepthSpan.textContent = maxDepth;

            // Start drawing the main trunk from the bottom center of the canvas
            // Initial length, initial angle (upwards), and max depth
            drawBranch(canvas.width / 2, canvas.height, canvas.height / 4, -Math.PI / 2, maxDepth);
        }

        // Event listener for the slider
        depthSlider.addEventListener('input', drawTree);

        // Initial draw
        drawTree();
    </script>

