                <h3>The Solution (Synchronization)</h3>
                <p>
                    This counter prevents the race condition by ensuring that only one update operation can be "active" at a time.
                </p>
                <p>
                    This version uses a simple <code>isUpdating</code> flag:
                    <ol>
                        <li>When a click occurs, it checks if an update is already in progress.</li>
                        <li>If not, it sets <code>isUpdating = true</code> and proceeds.</li>
                        <li>It <strong>reads the value and increments it synchronously</strong>, storing it in a variable.</li>
                        <li>Then, it starts the asynchronous delay.</li>
                        <li><strong>After the delay</strong>, it updates the display with the *already incremented* value.</li>
                        <li>Finally, it sets <code>isUpdating = false</code>, allowing the next pending update (if any) to proceed.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>Alternative Fixes:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Queuing:</strong> Add pending operations to a queue and process them sequentially.</li>
                        <li><strong>Atomic Updates:</strong> Some systems provide "compare-and-swap" operations.</li>
                        <li><strong>State Management:</strong> Use a central state management pattern (like Redux or Vuex) where updates are dispatched actions that modify state in a controlled, synchronous manner.</li>
                    </ul>
