        <h2>General REST Best Practices</h2>
        <div class="section">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Resource-Oriented URIs:</strong> URIs should identify resources (nouns), not actions (verbs). E.g., <code>/users</code> instead of <code>/getUsers</code>.</li>
                <li><strong>HTTP Methods for Actions:</strong> Use standard HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE) to define the action performed on the resource.</li>
                <li><strong>Consistent Naming:</strong> Use plural nouns for collection resources (e.g., <code>/users</code>) and singular nouns for specific resource instances (e.g., <code>/users/5</code>). Use kebab-case for multi-word paths (e.g., <code>/user-preferences</code>).</li>
                <li><strong>Statelessness:</strong> Each request from a client to server must contain all the information necessary to understand the request.</li>
                <li><strong>Proper Status Codes:</strong> Return appropriate HTTP status codes (2xx for success, 4xx for client errors, 5xx for server errors).</li>
                <li><strong>Hypermedia as the Engine of Application State (HATEOAS):</strong> (Advanced) Include links to related resources in responses to guide client navigation.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

