                    <li><strong>Verb in URL:</strong> The path <code>/createUser</code> includes the verb "createUser."</li>
                    <li><strong>Data in Query Parameters:</strong> Passing data for creation in query parameters is less secure, less flexible, and not suitable for complex data structures compared to sending data in the request body, which is standard for <code>POST</code> requests.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary><span class="method put">PUT</span> <code>/updateAllUsers</code></summary>
            <div class="content">
                <h3>Intended Purpose:</h3>
                <p>Update properties for all users in the system.</p>
                <h3>Design Problems:</h3>
                <ul class="problem-list">
                    <li><strong>Verb in URL:</strong> The path <code>/updateAllUsers</code> includes the verb "updateAllUsers."</li>
                    <li><strong>Ambiguous Semantics for <code>PUT</code>:</strong> <code>PUT</code> is typically used to *replace* a *specific* resource entirely, or to create a resource if it doesn't exist (idempotent update/create). Using it to "update all users" without specifying what "update" means (e.g., partial update, full replacement of the collection) is ambiguous and generally not a standard REST pattern for bulk operations.</li>
