        <ul>
            <li><strong>Use Nouns for Resources:</strong> Endpoints should represent resources (e.g., <code>/users</code>, <code>/products/123</code>).</li>
            <li><strong>Use HTTP Methods for Actions:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>GET</code>: Retrieve a resource or collection (safe, idempotent).</li>
                    <li><code>POST</code>: Create a new resource in a collection (not safe, not idempotent).</li>
                    <li><code>PUT</code>: Replace an entire resource or collection (idempotent).</li>
                    <li><code>PATCH</code>: Partially update a resource (not necessarily idempotent).</li>
                    <li><code>DELETE</code>: Remove a resource (idempotent).</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Consistent Pluralization:</strong> Use plural nouns for collections (<code>/users</code>) and singular for specific resources (<code>/users/{id}</code>).</li>
            <li><strong>Path Variables for IDs:</strong> Use <code>/users/{id}</code> to identify specific resources.</li>
            <li><strong>Query Parameters for Filtering/Sorting/Pagination:</strong> (e.g., <code>/users?status=active&sort=name</code>).</li>
            <li><strong>Use Request Body for Data:</strong> For <code>POST</code>, <code>PUT</code>, <code>PATCH</code>, send the data payload in the request body (typically JSON).</li>
            <li><strong>Meaningful Status Codes:</strong> Return appropriate HTTP status codes (e.g., <code>200 OK</code>, <code>201 Created</code>, <code>204 No Content</code>, <code>400 Bad Request</code>, <code>404 Not Found</code>, <code>500 Internal Server Error</code>).</li>
