        <h3>Why the "Garbage Collector Isn't Working" Diagnosis is Wrong</h3>
        <p>Your colleague's observation that their dashboard widget's memory grows over time, even after removing widgets, is a common symptom of a memory leak. However, attributing this directly to a "broken garbage collector" is usually incorrect. The JavaScript garbage collector (GC) is highly sophisticated and efficient at identifying and reclaiming memory that is *no longer reachable* from the root (e.g., the global object, active function call stacks).</p>

        <p>The problem demonstrated in the "Leaking Dashboard" is not that the GC isn't working, but rather that <strong>the application code is inadvertently maintaining references to objects that are no longer visually present or logically needed.</strong> As long as an object (like a DOM element or an event listener callback's closure) is reachable through *any* chain of references from the root, the GC will correctly assume it might still be needed and will *not* collect it.</p>

        <h4>Common Causes of JavaScript Memory Leaks (and what this demo illustrates):</h4>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <strong>Global Variables:</strong> Accidentally creating global variables (e.g., by forgetting <code>var</code>, <code>let</code>, or <code>const</code> in non-strict mode) can keep objects alive longer than intended. (Not the primary cause here, but related to root reachability).
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Unremoved Event Listeners:</strong> This is the primary leak demonstrated in the "Leaking Dashboard." When you add an event listener to a DOM element (e.g., <code>element.addEventListener('click', handler)</code>), the element holds a reference to the <code>handler</code> function. If the DOM element itself is removed from the DOM but the <code>handler</code> function (or the closure it creates) still holds references to other objects (like the widget's internal state or even the removed DOM element itself), then both the handler and the objects it references cannot be garbage collected. Even if the DOM element is removed from the UI, if the event listener array in the parent still holds a reference to it, it won't be collected.
                <p>In our "Leaking Dashboard", we're storing a direct reference to the DOM element in the <code>leakingWidgets</code> array. This array itself is reachable from the global scope. So, even when we call <code>removeChild</code>, the <code>widgetDiv</code> object still has an active reference in <code>leakingWidgets</code>, preventing it and its associated event listeners (and their closures) from being collected.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Closures:</strong> Closures are powerful but can be a source of leaks if not managed. A closure "remembers" the environment in which it was created. If a long-lived object (like a global variable or an active event listener) holds a reference to a closure, and that closure references other objects, those objects will also remain in memory.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Detached DOM Elements:</strong> If you remove an element from the DOM (e.g., <code>parentElement.removeChild(childElement)</code>) but still hold a JavaScript reference to that <code>childElement</code> in a variable, array, or object, it remains in memory. The GC cannot collect it because it's still reachable. Its children and any data associated with it (like event listeners) will also remain. This is a key part of the leak in the demo.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Timers (<code>setInterval</code>, <code>setTimeout</code>):</strong> If you set up a timer that repeatedly calls a function, and that function (or its closure) references objects, those objects will remain in memory as long as the timer is active. If you remove a widget but don't clear its associated timers, it can lead to a leak. (Not explicitly in this demo, but a common related issue).
            </li>
        </ol>

        <p><strong>The Fix:</strong> The "Fixed Dashboard" demonstrates the correct approach. When a widget is removed:</p>
