        <h2>Why Float Equality Fails for Financial Calculations</h2>
        <p>JavaScript (and most programming languages) uses the IEEE 754 standard for representing floating-point numbers (<code>number</code> type). This standard represents numbers in binary, which can perfectly represent numbers like 0.5 (1/2) or 0.25 (1/4).</p>
        <p>However, many common decimal fractions, like 0.1 (1/10), 0.2 (2/10), or 0.99 (99/100), cannot be represented exactly in binary. They become repeating fractions, similar to how 1/3 is 0.333... in decimal. When these numbers are stored, they are rounded to the nearest representable binary fraction, leading to tiny inaccuracies.</p>
        <p>For example, <code>0.1 + 0.2</code> in JavaScript doesn't equal <code>0.3</code>. It equals <code>0.30000000000000004</code>. If you then compare <code>(0.1 + 0.2) === 0.3</code>, it will evaluate to <code>false</code>.</p>
        <p>In financial calculations:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Totals:</strong> Accumulating these small errors can lead to a final total that is off by a tiny fraction of a cent, which can be significant in large-scale systems.</li>
            <li><strong>Comparisons:</strong> Using <code>===</code> for equality checks (e.g., "is the total exactly $9.98?") will often fail unexpectedly because the "target" number ($9.98) might be represented as <code>9.979999999999999</code> or <code>9.980000000000001</code> after calculations, making it not strictly equal to <code>9.98</code>.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>The Solution: Work with Integers (Cents)</h3>
        <p>The standard practice for financial calculations is to avoid floating-point numbers where precision is critical. Instead, represent monetary values as integers by scaling them up (e.g., store $4.99 as 499 cents). All calculations are then performed using these integers, which are exact.</p>
        <p>When displaying values to the user, convert the integer cents back to dollars and format them appropriately (e.g., <code>(499 / 100).toFixed(2)</code>).</p>
        <p>This approach guarantees accuracy for sums, subtractions, and comparisons, eliminating the subtle bugs caused by floating-point inaccuracies.</p>
        <p>For very complex financial systems or extremely large numbers, specialized libraries like <a href="https://mikemcl.github.io/decimal.js/" target="_blank">Decimal.js</a> or <a href="https://github.com/MikeMcl/big.js/" target="_blank">Big.js</a> (which work with arbitrary-precision decimals) or even JavaScript's native <code>BigInt</code> for whole numbers of cents are used.</p>
    </div>

